Table 3
 shows the CDAu0-3 catalysis. The fluorescence signal has a linear relationship with the catalyst concentration. As the Au content in CDAu0-CDAu3 increases, a strong chemical bond formed between the carbon dots and gold with rich electrons, which is beneficial to the plasmon resonance effect of Au atoms to makes the carbon dot fluorescence increase. The fluorescence intensity decreases after adding the excessive Au content such as CDAu3, that was unstable to aggregate and caused the catalytic activity decreased. By comparing the slopes of the linear equations of different catalytic systems, it is found that the slope of CDAu2 is the largest, that is, the CDAu2-H2O2-TMB has the strongest catalytic ability. When Apt was added to the system to inhibit its catalysis, the fluorescence signal weakened. The system ΔF404nm was negatively correlated with the Apt concentration. In the experiment, Au(III) was involved in the reaction to prepare Au-doped carbon dots, which glucose was used as the carbon source. Au3+ is attracted to the surface of the carbon dot by electrostatic interaction with the functional group. The d orbital of Au interacts with the p/π orbital of C to form a stable carbon dots. The carbon dot can catalyze the oxidation of TMB by H2O2 to form TMBOX with fluorescent product, gold electrons on CDAu are beneficial to the redox electrons-transfer of the H2O2-TMB redox reaction, thereby its catalytic activity enhanced (Fig. 4
). In addition, the DNAzyme shows catalysis of H2O2-TMB redox reaction due to π-π electrons accumulation on G-quadruplex/HM surface, and those electrons enhanced the redox electron transfer. However, the G-quadruplex of Pb(II)-Apt exhibited very weak enhancement on the redox reaction of H2O2-TMB (Fig. S6). In short, the catalysis is beneficial to both the nanoenzyme of CDAu2 and bioenzyme of G-quadruplex/HM.

Under the optimal conditions, the working curves of different Flu systems were plotted according to experimental methods. In the Apt-Pb(II)-CDAu0-3 systems (Table 4
                        ), the slope of the working curve of Apt-Pb(II)-CDAu2 system is the largest, so it is the most sensitive system for the detection of 0.067–0.4 μmol/L Pb2+ by fluorescence method, with regress equation of ΔF445nm = 687.86C + 6.8, correlation coefficient of 0.9894 and detection limit (DL) of 0.037μmol/LPb2+. In the Pb(II)-Apt-HM-CD–H2O2–TMB synergetic catalytic fluorescence analytical systems, the CDAu2 system has the largest slope, so it was chosen for fluorescence detection of 0.0005–0.46 μmol/L Pb2+, with regress equation of ΔF404nm = 1994.3C + 18.6, and a DL of 0.00025 μmol/L. This Flu method was compared to the reported methods, it has advantages of high sensitivity and selectivity. In addition, the microwave preparation of CDAu was simple and rapid (Table 5
                        ). Comparing to the reported methods for Pb2+ (Table 6
                        ), this method was high sensitivity, good selectivity and simple operation.
